stible riches, Dominique Charpin focuses here on the legal systems of Old Babylonian Mesopotamia and offers considerable insight into how writing and the law evolved together to forge the principles of authority, precedent, and documentation that dominate us to this day. As legal codes throughout the region evolved through advances in cuneiform writing, kings and governments were able to stabilize their control over distant realms and impose a common language—which gave rise to complex social systems overseen by magistrates, judges, and scribes that eventually became the vast empires of history books. Sure to attract any reader with an interest in the ancient Near East, as well as rhetoric, legal history, and classical studies, this book is an innovative account of the intertwined histories of law and language.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aCivilization, Assyro-Babylonian. 0aCuneiform writingxHistory. 0aDiplomatics, CuneiformzIraqxHistory. 0aLaw, Assyro-BabylonianxLanguage. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  atranslated work, translation, ancient mesopotamia, civilization, babylonian, assyrian, empire, code of hammurabi, history, historical, legal systems, legality, laws, government, governing, authority, power, precedent, documentation, cuneiform writing, royalty, kings, leadership, leaders, social system, diplomats, logo-syllabic script, wedge-shaped impressions, judges, magistrates, near east, rhetoric, classical studies, language, communication.1 aTodd, Jane Marie.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831106353860 cprintz978022610158340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226101590423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226101590/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package